Introduction to Functions

oddcount <- function(x) {
  k <- 0
  for(n in x) {
    if (n %% 2 == 1) k <- k + 1
  }
  return(k)
}

# function with default argument
g <- function(x, y = 2, z = T) {...}

Preview of Some Important R Data Structures

vector

x <- 8
x <- c(5, 12, 13)
mode(x)
## [1] "numeric"

character string

y <- "abc"
length(y) # important length is 1 !!!
## [1] 1
mode(y)
## [1] "character"
y <- c("abc", "89 23")
length(y)
## [1] 2
mode(y)
## [1] "character"

string操作：

u <- paste("abc", "de", "f")
u
## [1] "abc de f"
v <- strsplit(u, " ")
v
## [[1]]
## [1] "abc" "de"  "f"

Matrices

m <- rbind(c(1, 4), c(2, 2)) # row bind
m
##      [,1] [,2]
## [1,]    1    4
## [2,]    2    2
m[1,] # row 1
## [1] 1 4
m[,2] # column 2
## [1] 4 2

list

list类似于vector但它其中的元素可以是不同类型

x <- list(u = 2, v = "abc")
x
## $u
## [1] 2
## 
## $v
## [1] "abc"
x$v
## [1] "abc"
# 若不给每个元素取名会有如下形式
y <- list(2, "abc")
y
## [[1]]
## [1] 2
## 
## [[2]]
## [1] "abc"
y[1]
## [[1]]
## [1] 2
y[[1]]
## [1] 2

list常用于将包裹返回值，例如：

hn <- hist(Nile)

mode(hn)
## [1] "list"
print(hn)
## $breaks
##  [1]  400  500  600  700  800  900 1000 1100 1200 1300 1400
## 
## $counts
##  [1]  1  0  5 20 25 19 12 11  6  1
## 
## $density
##  [1] 0.0001 0.0000 0.0005 0.0020 0.0025 0.0019 0.0012 0.0011 0.0006 0.0001
## 
## $mids
##  [1]  450  550  650  750  850  950 1050 1150 1250 1350
## 
## $xname
## [1] "Nile"
## 
## $equidist
## [1] TRUE
## 
## attr(,"class")
## [1] "histogram"
str(hn) # 紧凑显示R对象， str表示 structure
## List of 6
##  $ breaks  : num [1:11] 400 500 600 700 800 900 1000 1100 1200 1300 ...
##  $ counts  : int [1:10] 1 0 5 20 25 19 12 11 6 1

##  $ mids    : num [1:10] 450 550 650 750 850 950 1050 1150 1250 1350
##  $ xname   : chr "Nile"
##  $ equidist: logi TRUE
##  - attr(*, "class")= chr "histogram"

data frames

data frames是一个list，每个元素都是一个vector，即以列观之类型相同，以行观之类型不同。

d <- data.frame(list(kids = c("Jack", "Jill"), ages = c(12, 10)))
d
##   kids ages
## 1 Jack   12
## 2 Jill   10

class

class的示例是带有attr(,"class")的list，泛化函数会根据class来做相应的处理。
class(robj)

Regression Analysis of Exam Grades

examquiz <- read.table("data/ExamsQuiz.txt")
class(examquiz)
## [1] "data.frame"
head(examquiz)
##    V1  V2  V3
## 1 2.0 3.3 4.0
## 2 3.3 2.0 3.7
## 3 4.0 4.3 4.0
## 4 2.3 0.0 3.3
## 5 2.3 1.0 3.3
## 6 3.3 3.7 4.0
lma <- lm(examquiz$V2 ~ examquiz$V1) # lm(examquiz[,2] ~ examquiz[,1]), lm(V2~V2, examquiz) ex2 = b+a*ex1
summary(lma)
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = examquiz$V2 ~ examquiz$V1)
## 
## Residuals:
##       1       2       3       4       5       6 
##  2.0284 -0.9392  0.4629 -1.6564 -0.6564  0.7608 
## 
## Coefficients:
##             Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)
## (Intercept)  -1.2939     2.5308  -0.511    0.636
## examquiz$V1   1.2828     0.8567   1.497    0.209
## 
## Residual standard error: 1.497 on 4 degrees of freedom
## Multiple R-squared:  0.3592, Adjusted R-squared:  0.199 
## F-statistic: 2.242 on 1 and 4 DF,  p-value: 0.2087
plot(examquiz$V1, examquiz$V2)
curve(x^lma$coefficients[2]+lma$coefficients[1], from = 2, to = 4, add = TRUE, col = "red")
